<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910422-0092</DOCNO><DOCID>910422-0092.</DOCID><HL>   Two Banks   In Connecticut   Report Losses   ---   Society for Savings, Suffield   Post Deficits in Quarter;   Norwich Bank Has Profit   ----   By Suzanne Alexander   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>04/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6A</SO><CO>   FFES NSSB SFCP SOCS</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>EASTERN U.S. BANKS (BAE)ALL REGIONAL BANKS (BAR)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)DIVIDENDS (DIV)EARNINGS (ERN)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><NS>DIVIDENDS (DIV)EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)</RE><LP>   Citing problem loans, two Connecticut banks postedfirst-quarter losses while another reported a sharp declinein earnings. But a fourth bank bucked the trend and reporteda profit.   Society for Savings Bancorp Inc. reported a first-quarterloss of $8 million, or 67 cents a share, and said it willrecommend suspension of its 7.5-cent quarterly dividend. Thedividend had been reduced from 15 cents in January. TheHartford-based bank holding company had net income of $4.7million, or 40 cents a share, in the first quarter last year.</LP><TEXT>   Society for Savings, which has assets of $3.7 billion,said nonperforming assets rose to $203.8 million as of March31 from $189 million on Dec. 31, 1990.   Suffield Financial Corp., based in Suffield, Conn.,reported a first-quarter loss of $1.7 million, or 28 cents ashare, versus a loss of $3.2 million, or 54 cents a share, inthe year-ago period. Suffield said cost-cutting and incomerelated to increased residential mortgage production enabledit to narrow its loss.   However, Suffield, with assets of $545.4 million, said itsnonperforming assets rose to $66.6 million as of March 31from $51 million at year end.   First Federal Savings andamp; Loan Association of East Hartfordreported a 77% decline in net income for the first quarter,primarily because of &quot;larger than anticipated&quot; additions toits provision for possible losses.   The bank holding company, with assets of $480.9 million,had net income of $151,000, or six cents a share, comparedwith $653,000, or 28 cents a share, in the year-earlier firstquarter.   First Federal said its nonperforming loans rose to $4.9million as of March 31 from $3.7 million as of Dec. 31. Itsaid it added $975,000 to its loan-loss reserves, including$650,000 &quot;to provide for possible losses on assets which arecurrently performing.&quot;   First Federal declared a seven-cent quarterly dividend,payable May 16 to holders of record May 8.   Norwich Financial Corp., based in Norwich, Conn., reporteda profit in the first quarter versus a year-ago loss,primarily because of a lower provision for loan losses and$404,000 in recoveries from problem assets.   Norwich, with assets of $602 million, had net income of$840,000, or 16 cents a share, compared with a loss of $14.3million, or $2.75 a share, in the year-ago period. Norwich'sprovision for losses on loans and foreclosed property was$750,000 in the quarter. Nonperforming assets at the end ofthe first quarter were $47.8 million compared with $47.4million as of Dec. 31.</TEXT></DOC>